First, let's analyze the problem. The trajectory of a classical harmonic oscillator is given by:
`trajectory (IC : InitialConditions) : Time → Space 1 := fun t => cos (S.ω * t) • IC.x₀ + (sin (S.ω * t)/S.ω) • IC.v₀`

The velocity is the derivative of the trajectory with respect to time. We need to compute this derivative and set it to zero to find when the velocity is zero.

The derivative of `cos(S.ω * t)` with respect to `t` is `-S.ω * sin(S.ω * t)`.
The derivative of `sin(S.ω * t)` with respect to `t` is `S.ω * cos(S.ω * t)`.

So the velocity is:
`∂ₜ (IC.trajectory S) t = -S.ω * sin(S.ω * t) • IC.x₀ + S.ω * cos(S.ω * t) • IC.v₀ / S.ω`
`∂ₜ (IC.trajectory S) t = -S.ω * sin(S.ω * t) • IC.x₀ + cos(S.ω * t) • IC.v₀`

Setting this to zero:
`-S.ω * sin(S.ω * t) • IC.x₀ + cos(S.ω * t) • IC.v₀ = 0`
`S.ω * sin(S.ω * t) • IC.x₀ = cos(S.ω * t) • IC.v₀`
`tan(S.ω * t) = IC.v₀ / (S.ω * IC.x₀)`

This gives us the condition when the velocity is zero. Now we need to relate this to the norm of the position.

The position at time `t` is:
